quran[17]{c,v,t,f}:
23,43,"No nation can outstrip its term, nor can it put it back."
23,44,"Then We sent Our Messengers in succession. Whenever a Messenger came to his people they rejected him, calling him a liar. Thereupon, We made each people to follow the other (to its doom), reducing them to mere tales (of the past). Scourged be the people who do not believe! {1}",footnotes:1:That is
23,45,"Then We sent Moses and his brother Aaron with Our Signs and a clear authority {1}",footnotes:1:The use of a manifest Authority along with Our signs may either mean that the signs were a clear proof that they were Messengers of Allah
23,46,"to Pharaoh and to his chiefs, but they behaved superciliously and they were haughty. {1}",footnotes:1:The words in the text may either mean: (1) They were highly arrogant and tyrannous people
23,47,"They said: "Shall we put faith in two mortals like ourselves {1} when their people are slaves to us?" {2}",footnotes:1:a For explanation
23,48,"So they rejected them, calling them liars, and they too eventually became of those that were destroyed. {1}",footnotes:1:For further details of the story of Prophet Moses (peace be upon him) and Pharaoh
23,49,"And We gave Moses the Book that people might be guided by it."
23,50,"And We made Mary's son, and his mother, a Sign, {1} and We gave them refuge on a lofty ground, a peaceful site with springs flowing in it. {2}",footnotes:1:The wording “We made the son of Mary and his mother a sign” is very significant
23,51,"Messengers! {1} Partake of the things that are clean, and act righteously. {2} I know well all that you do.",footnotes:1:“Pure things” implies that they should be wholesome and must have been earned in lawful ways. Here the instruction
23,52,"This community of yours is one community, and I am your Lord; so hold Me alone in fear. {1}",footnotes:1:The original Arabic word ummat (community) comprises those individuals who have some basic things common among them. All the Messengers of Allah belonged to one and the same community because they had the same creed and the same religion and the same message. See also (Surah Al-Baqarah
23,53,"But people later cut up their religion into bits, each group rejoicing in what they have. {1}",footnotes:1:This is not a mere statement of a fact
23,54,"So leave them immersed in their heedlessness till an appointed time. {1}",footnotes:1:There is a gap between (verses 53 and 54)
23,55,"Do they fancy that Our continuing to give them wealth and children (means) that"
23,56,"We are busy lavishing on them all kinds of good? Nay, they do not perceive the reality of the matter. {1}",footnotes:1:This question has been posed as a proof of the main theme of the Surah. It is meant to remove their misconception of success
23,57,"Surely those who stand in awe for fear of their Lord, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
23,58,"who have full faith in the Signs of their Lord; {1}",footnotes:1:Signs here means both divine revelations to the Prophets and the signs found in man’s own self and in the universe around him. To believe in the verses of the Book is to affirm them
23,59,"who associate none with their Lord in His Divinity, {1}",footnotes:1:Though belief in the revelations itself ingrains the doctrine of Tauhid in the hearts
